He left one of those pride themed Lego sets on my brother's bed for him to come home to after school. Never made it a big deal between them, or anyone else in the family, just went on with his little acts of love like he always had. Showed my brother that he'd been seen.

But my brother DID have that experience, which is something I'm eternally thankful for. He at least got to talk to our dad and tell him about who he was (is) in a way that made him feel happy, safe, proud. And you know how my dad responded?

Anyway, I never had the chance to tell my dad that I wasn't straight on my own terms. It was ripped out of me by circumstances beyond my control and that has always cut me really deeply. I wanted to talk to him about it in my own way on my own time, but life had other plans.

For my brother it was the same, but with Lego sets. Lego has always been my brother's favorite thing ever since he was little and my dad funded his Lego addiction as much as he'd funded my train boy adolescence.

He just knew that I knew it was his way of supporting my goofy little hobby and in doing so he was saying he loved me. To this day I think it was a great little thing he did. It was his quiet way of saying I see you, I know who you are, and I love you.

I remember when I was younger I would frequently walk into my room and see new stuff for my train set just laying on my bed. He never liked to make a big deal of things and bring attention to the gifts; he'd just leave them there and know that I knew they were from him.

Quick thread because I'm annoyed lol.
